---
import { withBase } from '../../lib/url';
import Prose from '../../layouts/Prose.astro';
import ReadingWorksheet from '../../components/course/ReadingWorksheet.astro';
import { TOOLS } from '../../lib/tools';

const tool = TOOLS.find((t) => t.slug === 'reading-worksheet')!;
---

<Prose
  title={tool.title}
  description={tool.description}
  crumbs={[{ name: 'Tools', href: '/tools/' }, { name: tool.title }]}
  kicker="Practice Tools"
>
  <p>
    Reading a chart is a procedure before it is an art: the question and its house, the Witnesses
    and Judge, the significators and their springings, the scan for perfection, the review of
    aspects and company, and the weighing that becomes an answer. This worksheet walks that
    canonical order one step at a time and assembles your notes into a draft reading, the same
    instrument the course unlocks across
    <a href={withBase('/course/perfection-of-the-figure/')}>Lesson 7</a> and completes in
    <a href={withBase('/course/the-finished-reading/')}>Lesson 10</a>.
  </p>
  <p>
    Without JavaScript every step renders at once, which makes the page a printable worksheet.
    Paper is how it should be used in any case: the course's standing practice is the written
    reading, filed in a journal where the answer can one day face its outcome. The method
    itself is set out at <a href={withBase('/techniques/reading-the-figure/')}>Reading the Figure</a> and
    <a href={withBase('/techniques/modes-of-perfection/')}>The Modes of Perfection</a>; for practice
    material, <a href={withBase('/course/charts/')}>the course charts</a> carry eleven canonical casts with
    standing questions.
  </p>

  <ReadingWorksheet />
</Prose>
